  "text": "In this case, all the inferred t i are scalar multiples of one another. Therefore a singular-value decomposition (SVD) of the set of rate matrices should show that the largest singular value is sufficient to describe the set of rate matrices [CITATION_1] . [64] . In CSVD, the origin of the coordinate system corresponds to the average Q, not the zero matrix. Therefore the axes corresponding to large singular values need not correspond to directions in which the original rate matrices are related by scalar multiplication. This coordinate system is particularly suited to detecting changes in Q (due to HGT, for example).",
